Integration test for smart-profile rendering, ported from `test/smart.test.ts`; it exercises `render_smart`, `render_plain`, and `build_smart_dict` against the real `dict.steno` corpus loaded from the repo root (`CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR/../../dict.steno`), not a fixture file.

The corpus is parsed once per test via `typed()` (`parse_source` + `expand_dict`), so every test implicitly depends on current corpus contents for the specific strokes it looks up (`STKWR-PBGS/TPH-FLT`, `STKWR-BGS`, `STKWR-T/PR/STR`, `STKWRUPBGS/TPH-FLT`, `STKWR-PBGS/PR-FLT`, `STKWR-RBGT/S`, `STKWR-RBGT/HR`, `STKWR-RPBT`) — if any of these strokes are renamed or removed in `dict.steno`, the corresponding test breaks with a lookup failure, not an assertion mismatch. Three original upstream assertions (`STKWR-LT`) no longer apply because the corpus repurposed that stroke to a `let` binding; rather than dropping coverage, this file synthesizes the old fixture standalone via `terminal_entry`/`template_literal`, bypassing the corpus and `parse_source` entirely to build a `TypedEntry` directly from `parse_template("` ` $ { % 0 } ` `", 1)` and a hand-built `Entry`/`EntryFlags::default()`. Anyone touching `TypedEntry` or `Entry`'s field set must update `terminal_entry` in lockstep or this synthesized path silently diverges from what `expand_dict` would produce.

Key invariants asserted: smart rendering drops the auto-closed trailing brace/bracket for function bodies and index literals but keeps interior closers (type-over behavior) and keeps both angle brackets for generics (since editors don't auto-close `<`); non-terminal entries and bracket-free constructs (ternaries) render identically under `render_smart` and `render_plain`; `@literal` blocks use a distinct "struct emitter" path in smart mode (no `\}` in output, navigates via `{#Down...}`) versus plain mode (which types every closing brace). `full_smart_dict` asserts `build_smart_dict` over the whole corpus produces zero collisions and more than 1000 keys — a regression here signals a corpus-wide dictionary-build problem, not a single-entry bug.